**Introduction**  
The purpose of this project was aimed at creating a library management system designed to replicate the functionality of a basic library computer system. The user is prompted to login or create an account on the library system after which the user will be able to check out books, return books, search for books, and check the due dates of already-checked out books. The user can also choose to logout and exit the system or login with a different account. 

**Program Structure**  
The program is composed of three header files–library.h, accounts.h, and system.h–each which contain different classes that collectively allow for the library management program to function. Each of these header files store the utility functions in separate cpp filesa. The library.h header has two classes: *Book* which stores basic information about each book such as the title, author, and ISBN, and *Library* which stores all of the books in the library in a single vector and handles different functions such as adding/removing books, searching for books, and checking out/returning books. The accounts.h header also has two classes. *Account* stores the username and password of the user as well as a list of all the checked out books for the user, while 

![][image2]  
*Figure 1: Relationship between classes and member functions*

also having basic functions to add and remove checked out books from the list and printing the list of checked out books. *AccountList* stores all of the accounts in a single vector much like *Library* and can add/remove accounts, validate accounts (check if the username entered corresponds to the right password), and searches for accounts. The final header *system.h* corresponding of four functions brings everything together visually   
in the terminal–*importLibrary* starts by creating the library by taking a CSV file and storing it into a library, *createInterface* asks the user for the username/password or for registering a new account, *checkUser* validates whether the user entered an existing username that matches to the right password, and *startMenu* shows the user options to choose from after successfully logging in and performs the selections from the user. **Figure 1\.** above shows a visual representation of what the structure is and what the relationship between the classes of the program is like. As seen from the figure, *system.h* taps into the *library* and *accounts* multiple times to be able to access and modify the data that is stored in the two vectors.

**Program Flow of Logic**  
*Library Creation*: The program starts by assuming that a CSV file exists in which data for the books of the library are stored. This CSV file stores the title, author, ISBN, book availability, and return date of each book. All the data for these books are read and stored as *Book* objects which are then stored in a vector–this is the library. 

*User Login*: The program will then prompt the user for a username and password; here the path of logic is split into four. First, if the user types an incorrect username and password five times, the program will automatically exit. Second, if the user inputs the word “exit” when typing the username, the program will exit. Third, if the user inputs the number “1” when typing the username, the program will prompt the user to create a new username and password and the user will be directed back to the login. Fourth, if the username and password match, the user will be taken to the start menu. 

*Start Menu*: After the user successfully logs in, the user is given five different options as shown below, which the user can select by inputting numbers from 1 to 5\.

1. Check out: the user can check out a book by typing in the title of the book or the ISBN number associated with that book. A confirmation message will appear with the details of the book to check if the user wants to continue to check out the book. If the confirmation is denied, the user will be taken back to the start menu. If the confirmation is accepted, the due date will be updated two weeks from the time that the user confirmed to check out the book, and the user will be taken back to the start menu.  
2. Search: the user can search for information on a certain book by inputting the title of the book or the ISBN associated with the book. The user will then be returned back to the menu.  
3. View checked out books and due dates: the console will display the titles and due dates of the current checked out books for that user. The user will then be returned back to the start menu.  
4. Return book: the user can return a book that he or she has checked out by inputting the title of the book or the ISBN number associated with the book. A confirmation message will appear with the details of the book to check if the user wants to continue to return the book. If the confirmation is denied, the user will be returned back to the start menu. If the confirmation is confirmed, the due date of the book will be updated to an empty value, and the user will be returned back to the start menu.  
5. Logout: the user will be returned back to the login page, where the user has the option to login again, login with a different username and password, or exit. 

A visual representation of the functionality and logic of the library management system is displayed in **Figure 2\.** where the sequences of steps and decisions needed to perform a process are shown.

**Approach**  
Now, a more detailed description describing the approach of the code will be explained, highlighting optimizations of speed and memory throughout the code.

***Library.h***  
The *Book* class and the *Library* class in the *library.h* were the first to be implemented. A book being stored inside a computer library management system should contain basic information that can help the user access the book (the title and ISBN number) and know more about the book (the author, the availability, and the author). To access these private variables, getters and setters were implemented so that the variables can be accessed and modified; here, the getters and setters were implemented as inline 

| //Getter for book titleinline string getTitle() const { return title; }//Setter for book titleinline void setTitle(string title) { this\-\>title \= title; } |
| :---- |

| //Add bookvoid Library::addBook(const Book& book) {   //Allocate new memory   Book\* newBook \= new Book(book.title, book.author, book.ISBN, book.availability, book.dueDate);   library.push\_back(newBook);   cout \<\< book.title \<\< " added successfully\!" \<\< endl;   numBooks++;}//Removes book using title & ISBNvoid Library::removeBook(string text) {   for(int i \= 0; i \< numBooks; i++) {       if(library\[i\]-\>title \== text || library\[i\]-\>ISBN \== text) {           cout \<\< library\[i\]-\>title \<\< " removed successfully\!" \<\< endl;           //Deallocate memory           delete library\[i\];           library.erase(library.begin() \+ i);           numBooks--;           return;       }   }   cout \<\< "Book not found." \<\< endl;} |
| :---- |

functionsa to optimize the runtime of the program. Since getters and setters are very short functions, by inlining, the function can replace the code of the function being called–this reduces the time to push the function in and out of the stack1. The code displayed on the left is the getter and setter function for the title of the object *Book*, which will either return the title of the book or set the title of the book to a different name. The books were then stored into a vector in the *Library* class. To be able to access each different book in the library, the addresses of each *Book* object was stored inside the vector; this way a certain address can be called which stores the title, author, ISBN, availability, and due date. Using pointersb, both memory and speed can be optimized through the use of dynamic memory allocation. Pointers have the ability to be resized, meaning that they are dynamic; for example, the addBook function allows memory to be allocated for a new *Book* object to be added to the library, while the removeBook function allows memory to be deallocated from the heap as they are removed from the library. Pointers also allow direct access to the memory locations which can be faster than accessing data indirectly through functions or by copying data between locations2. The code shown on the right displays the member functions addBook and removeBook that optimize the program through the use of dynamic memory allocation. The *Library* class also has other member functions that utilize the library vector. The getBook function allows the memory address of a certain book to be returned if a book title or ISBN number is passed as a parameter. The printBookInformation function displays through the console the information of all of the variables of the books for the user to see. This function is then utilized by the searchBook function which, if a book title or ISBN number is passed as a parameter, the information for that certain book will be displayed using function printBookInformation. The boolean function searchBookExistence will take a book title or ISBN number as a parameter and return true or false depending on whether that certain book associated with the text parameter is within the vector library. The checkoutBook and returnBook function also take in a book title or ISBN number as a   
parameter, search for the book with the given input, and update the book due date and availability as needed (for the checkoutBook function, an additional parameter that takes in the date is also implemented).

The *Account* class and the *AccountList* class in *Account.h* have a very similar relationship in comparison to the relationship of how *Book* and *Library* work together. The *Account* class has attributes username, password, the list of checked out books, and the number of checked out books. The member functions of this class all relate to the list of checked out books: addCheckedOutBook takes in a *Book* object and stores it in the vector of checked out books, removeCheckedOutBook removes a book from the list given the book title or ISBN number, printCheckedOutBooks iterates through the whole list and prints out the title and due date of each book, and checkBook returns a true or false value on whether a book exists in the list given a book title or ISBN number. A key highlight for the member functions is the use of the key “const”. Constant member functionsa are important because they do not permit any change for the values of the attributes in the class that the member function is part of3. The code on the right displays the printCheckedOutBooks function that iterates through the vector to print the title and due date of each book. Since this function shouldn’t make any changes to any of the attributes of the class, it is important to keep this function constant so that it is a “read-only” function. The *AccountList* also takes in a vector of pointers of *Account* type much like *Library* does with *Book*. It also has member functions that allow for the additional and removal of accounts from the vector of account addresses, a searchAccount function that returns the address of a certain account given the username as a parameter, and a boolean validateAccount function that takes in a username and password as parameter and iterates through the vector to see whether there is an account that matches both the username and password. An important attribute when working with pointers is the use of dynamic memory allocation with constructors and destructors as well. When an object of type *AccountList* is created, a constructor initializes an object (memory is allocated), so it is important to also deallocate memory using the delete feature which can be done with a destructorb. This deallocation of memory is useful for memory optimization as it will free up memory from the heap that can be used for other processes4. The code above highlights how the destructor for the *AccountList* iterates through the whole vector, deleting all of the accounts (in case there are any that

were missed when using the removeAccount function) and also resets the number of accounts back to zero. 

| class Book {   private:       string title;       string author;       string ISBN;       bool availability;       string dueDate;       friend class Account;       friend class Library;    ... }; |
| :---- |

A common attribute for all of these classes was its reliance on the *Book* class. Most of the member functions from the *Account* and *Library* class needed constant access to the attributes of the *Book* class, but since it is not optimal for these functions to access the attributes through the continued use of getters and setters, the *Account* and *Library* class was declared a frienda of the *Book* class. By declaring *Account* and *Library* as a friend of *Book*, these classes gain access to the private members of the *Book* class. This helps optimize with speed since these fiend classes can directly modify the attributes without the use of public functions such as getters or setters. These classes have interrelated data members which also allows for extended storage while maintaining encapsulation in case other functions outside of the class try to modify the private members of *Book5*.

The final *system.h* provides a visual output to the console for the user and puts all of these classes together to use. Focusing on the startMenu function which the user gains access to after having successfully logged in, the program only accepts inputs of numbers from 1 to 5\. Since there will be an error if the user inputs something else such as a string, to handle such exceptions try, throw, and catchb was implemented. The code on the right shows how this works: first, an input will “tried” to be stored inside the variable selection which is of type *int*. If the user inputs a selection that is invalid (which in this case is any input that is not an integer), the exception will be thrown and caught by the catch block, which outputs “Invalid input”. Using these try/catch blocks helps to distinguish regular if/else statements from error handling and can help with grouping different types of errors6. **Solution**  
In this final section, different obstacles that were faced when creating the library management system and their solutions will be addressed. The first issue was addressing how to create a library. Since it is tedious work to create numerous *Book* objects each with different attributes, the solution was to create a CSV file in which the data for the books could be stored. Using the library \<fstream\>, an infilea object could be created that opens the CSV file and reads the data from it. The data for each line would contain the attributes needed for a *Book*, which could then be transferred into a *Book* object and added to the library. This would be an efficient way to create the library without the manual declaration of what could be thousands of books. 

The second issue was a more technical issue in which if the user inputs a string “apple” instead requested for a number, the error message would appear five times since each character was thought of as an individual input. Using the code below, any input buffer that there may have been was ignored for the largest streamsize available or until a newline character was detected. This was if a string of many characters was inputted by the user, it would output on error of the string and not many based on the number of characters.

| cin.ignore(numeric\_limits\<streamsize\>::max(), '\\n'); |
